# SwiftUI Conventions — {{.ProjectName}}

## Views

- Views are functions of state — no side effects in the `body` property
- Extract subviews when `body` exceeds ~40 lines; prefer computed properties for simple extractions
- Use `@State` for view-local state, `@Bindable` for ViewModel bindings, `@Environment` for injected dependencies
- Never put business logic in a View — delegate to the ViewModel

## Observation

- Use `@Observable` (Observation framework) for all new ViewModels — not `ObservableObject` / `@Published`
- Mark stored properties that shouldn't trigger updates with `@ObservationIgnored`
- Pass ViewModels to child views as parameters, not through `@Environment` (unless truly app-wide)

## Lifecycle

- Use `.task` for async work on appear, not `.onAppear` — `.task` handles cancellation automatically
- Use `.task(id:)` when async work should restart when a value changes
- Prefer `.onChange(of:)` over manual state diffing for reacting to state changes

## Accessibility

- Every interactive element must have an accessibility label
- Use `.accessibilityLabel()` for custom labels, `.accessibilityHint()` for non-obvious actions
- Test with VoiceOver in Simulator to verify navigation flow
- Group related elements with `.accessibilityElement(children: .combine)` where appropriate

## Animation

- Prefer implicit animations with `.animation(.default, value:)` scoped to specific state changes
- Use `withAnimation` only for coordinated multi-view transitions
- Keep durations under 0.35s for UI state changes; use spring animations for interactive gestures
- Always provide `.contentTransition(.numericText())` for animated number changes

## Layout

- Prefer `LazyVStack`/`LazyHStack` inside `ScrollView` for long lists over `List` when custom styling is needed
- Use `ViewThatFits` for adaptive layouts before reaching for `GeometryReader`
- Avoid `GeometryReader` in scrollable content — it causes layout thrashing
